            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Chloe Miller\u2019s professional calling is a direct reflection of her upbringing in Cupertino. The daughter of a pragmatic American hardware engineer and a creative South Korean ceramicist, Chloe was raised in a home where structured logic coexisted with expressive art. This duality defined her path, steering her away from pure engineering and toward the tangible, human-centric world of industrial design. After completing her undergraduate degree at UC Davis, she moved to San Francisco to pursue her master's at the California College of the Arts, a decision that felt like a true homecoming.\n\nHer career began on the design floor of a consumer electronics company, where her ability to speak the language of both artists and engineers quickly set her apart. She thrived on translating abstract concepts into manufacturable realities. A key turning point came three years ago when she was asked to lead a struggling project. She successfully navigated complex supply chain issues and clashing personalities, delivering the product on time and earning a promotion to Product Development Manager. Now, she orchestrates the entire product lifecycle, from initial sketch to final packaging, a role that perfectly suits her organized yet inventive nature.\n\nChloe lives in a meticulously curated one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Sunset. Her daily routine begins with a ride on the N-Judah, a 3.8-mile journey to her SoMa office where she sips her coffee while listening to design podcasts. Evenings are for decompressing\u2014either a run through Golden Gate Park, which she considers her backyard, or cooking with her long-term partner, Leo, a landscape architect. Their shared passion for creating beautiful, functional spaces is a cornerstone of their relationship.\n\nSocially, Chloe maintains a close-knit circle of friends from grad school and former colleagues. They bond over gallery openings, trying new restaurants in the Mission, and weekend hikes in Marin. Looking forward, Chloe dreams of launching her own small company focused on sustainable, ethically sourced home goods. She feels a growing desire to build something that is entirely her own, a legacy that honors both the engineer and the artist who raised her."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers watching her mother fix a celadon bowl that had cracked in the kiln. Her father suggested discarding it, but her mother meticulously repaired the fissure with gold lacquer, transforming the flaw into a beautiful feature. Chloe, only ten, felt a profound sense of understanding. It wasn't about hiding imperfections, but honoring them. This single act became the foundation of her design philosophy: that utility and beauty, strength and fragility, could coexist and even enhance one another. It was the first time she saw her parents' worlds merge perfectly.\n\n2.\nThe first time Chloe walked into her graduate studio at CCA, the air smelled of sawdust, ozone from the laser cutters, and wet clay. After years of feeling slightly out of place in pure engineering, that sensory cocktail felt like coming home. She saw sketches taped next to circuit diagrams and felt a wave of relief so powerful it almost buckled her knees. This was it. This was the language she was born to speak, and she had finally found the place where everyone else spoke it, too.\n\n3.\nIt was 2 AM, on a tense video call with the factory in Shenzhen. The project was failing. Frustrated, Chloe grabbed a whiteboard, sketched a new housing assembly that solved the engineering problem without sacrificing the design, and held it to the tiny webcam. She saw a flicker of understanding in the factory manager\u2019s tired eyes\u2014the first breakthrough in weeks. The resulting success and promotion were validating, but that moment of pure, bilingual problem-solving is what gave her the unshakeable confidence she carries today.\n\n4.\nTheir first weekend in the Inner Sunset apartment, she and Leo assembled a notoriously complex Swedish bookshelf. He, the landscape architect, saw the macro-structure, planning its placement for room flow. She, the industrial designer, obsessed over the seamlessness of the joinery and the alignment of each dowel. They worked in a silent, joyful rhythm. In that moment, surrounded by boxes, Chloe knew their relationship was built on this shared language\u2014a mutual reverence for creating beautiful, functional spaces. It felt like building a life, not just furniture.\n\n5.\nDuring a foggy evening run, she stopped to catch her breath by Stow Lake. She watched the ducks glide across the glassy water, the N-Judah rumbling faintly in the distance. A wave of discontent with corporate compromises washed over her, followed by a sudden, sharp clarity. She envisioned her own brand of home goods\u2014sustainable, honest, and imbued with the spirit of her parents. The park wasn't just her backyard; it was the place her future finally took shape, quiet and resolute as the fog settling around her."
